    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="background">

There is a case study where a video game publisher web site was being developed 
(Preece et al., 2002, p. 283)</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="11" relname="span">  The video game publisher team felt that they really needed 
to get in touch with users to be able to understand the essence of gaming.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="10" relname="condition">  I suspect that 
if the team continued with what they thought would be the proper usability principles for 
this group of people,</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="9" relname="span"> the web site might have had to be reworked after the fact.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="12" relname="span">  It has 
been shown that different principles have been developed for different situations, such as 
the HOMERUN principles for web sites (Preece et. al, p. 409),</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="4" relname="restatement">  and I suspect that each 
environment has its own principles that have come about to meet the needs of the 
environment.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="13" relname="span">  There might have been less user interaciton by the video game publisher 
team</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="7" relname="condition"> if they were familiar with the environment.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="14" relname="concession">  With that said, the lack of familiarity of 
an environment might be a good reason to have users more involved in a design.

</segment>
